subject: Re: Why doesn't JUnit count asserts
msgSnippet: If you change the comments, the test can be constructive. public void testSomeThing() { // Placeholder for completeness and future tests // // The
messageBody:
If you change the comments, the test can be constructive.

public void testSomeThing()
{
// Placeholder for completeness and future tests
//
// The tests.other.UsesSomeThingTestSuite and
// tests.other.SomeThingEqualityTestSuite
// suites perform exhaustive tests on someThing.
// When I think of others aspect to test, I'll add them here.
}


--- In junit@y..., Keith Ray <keith.ray@e...> wrote:
> The following test case has no assertions...
>
> public void testSomeThing()
> {
> // fill in this code someday... in the meantime,
> // give everyone a false sense of security because
> // this counts as a passed test.
> }
>
> ...should I be worried that this test isn't good enough?
